# WCAG Landmark Navigation

Use semantic landmarks to provide consistent keyboard and screen-reader navigation.

- Each rendered page must contain exactly one `main` landmark with `id="main"`.
- The skip link must be the first focusable element on the page and target `#main`.
- Skip link should be visually hidden by default and visible on focus (e.g., `sr-only focus:not-sr-only`).
- Put site-level chrome in semantic landmarks:
  - `header` for site header area
  - `nav` for primary navigation
  - `footer` for site footer area
- Prefer semantic elements over `div` + landmark `role`.
- If more than one `nav` exists, each must have a distinct `aria-label`.
- `main` must wrap all primary page content, not partial fragments.
- Do not create nested `main` landmarks.

## Verification Checklist

- Keyboard: `Tab` reaches skip link first and activating it moves focus to `#main`.
- Automated: run axe and resolve any "Landmark" violations.
- Route-level: verify landmark structure on each page template/layout path.

## Example (Nuxt/Tailwind)

```vue
<a href="#main" class="sr-only focus:not-sr-only">Skip to main content</a>
<header>...</header>
<nav aria-label="Main navigation">...</nav>
<main id="main" tabindex="-1"><NuxtPage /></main>
<footer>...</footer>
```
